[4] The Zombie: "What is a zombie process in Linux? Can you kill it with kill -9? If not, how do you get rid of it?"
A zombie process in Linux is a process that has completed execution but still has an entry in the process table. 
This happens because the parent process has not yet read the exit status of the child process. 
A zombie process cannot be killed with kill -9 because it is not actively running; it is already dead. 
To get rid of a zombie process, you need to terminate the parent process or have the parent process read the exit status of the child process using wait(). 
Once the parent process acknowledges the termination of the child process, the zombie process will be removed from the process table.

Commands:

ps -el | grep Z

kill -9 <zombie_pid>    -> does noting. Because the process is already dead.

ps -o ppid= -p <zombie_pid>    -> find the parent

ps -fp 1000     -> check the parent





